",{"#text":1539},{"given-names":16130},[16131],{"#text":8173},{"#text":887},{"#text":887},{"name":16135},[16136,16137,16140,16141,16144],{"#text":1539},{"surname":16138},[16139],{"#text":572},{"#text":1539},{"given-names":16142},[16143],{"#text":7112},{"#text":887},{"#text":887},{"name":16147},[16148,16149,16152,16153,16156],{"#text":1539},{"surname":16150},[16151],{"#text":7341},{"#text":1539},{"given-names":16154},[16155],{"#text":7478},{"#text":887},{"#text":887},{"name":16159},[16160,16161,16165,16166,16169],{"#text":1539},{"surname":16162},[16163],{"#text":16164},"Maeda",{"#text":1539},{"given-names":16167},[16168],{"#text":6281},{"#text":887},{"#text":887},{"etal":16172},[],{"#text":861},{"@_person-group-type":5717},{"#text":3544},{"year":16177},[16178],{"#text":4994},{"#text":4303},{"article-title":16181},[16182],{"#text":16183},"Sponge Transgenic Mouse Model Reveals Important Roles for the MicroRNA-183 (miR-183)/96/182 Cluster in Postmitotic Photoreceptors of the Retina.",{"source":16185},[16186],{"italic":16187},[16188],{"#text":15723},{"volume":16190},[16191],{"#text":16192},"286",{"fpage":16194},[16195],{"#text":16196},"31749",{"#text":5813},{"lpage":16199},[16200],{"#text":16201},"31760",{"#text":2138},{"pub-id":16204,":@":16207},[16205],{"#text":16206},"10.1074/jbc.M111.259028",{"@_pub-id-type":5748},{"pub-id":16209,":@":16212},[16210],{"#text":16211},"21768104",{"@_pub-id-type":5754},{"@_citation-type":5756},{"#text":946},[16216,16217,16218,16219,16220,16221],{"surname":16101,"givenNames":14704},{"surname":16114,"givenNames":7225},{"surname":16127,"givenNames":8173},{"surname":572,"givenNames":7112},{"surname":7341,"givenNames":7478},{"surname":16164,"givenNames":6281},[],[16224,16241,16278,16311,16336,16360,16383,16541,17637],{"id":1748,"type":16225,"title":1770,"description":16226,"descriptionNodes":16227,"altText":19,"imageUrl":1797},"Figure","PCR-sequencing strategy for mutation screening in the miR-183/96/182 cluster. (A) Schematic illustration of the miR-183/96/182 cluster in relation to the PCR and sequencing primers. Pre-miR-183/96 is amplified by 183/96-F1/R1 and sequenced by primers of 183/96-F2 and 183/96-R2. pre-miR-182 was amplified with primers 182-F0/R3, and sequenced by 182-F1 and 182-R2. The numbers above the double arrows indicate the sizes of the marked fragments in base pairs (bp). (B) Examples of amplification products.",[16228,16229,16240],{"#text":887},{"p":16230},[16231,16232,16235,16236,16239],{"#text":1778},{"bold":16233},[16234],{"#text":1782},{"#text":1784},{"bold":16237},[16238],{"#text":1788},{"#text":1790},{"#text":861},{"id":2085,"type":16225,"title":2102,"description":16242,"descriptionNodes":16243,"altText":19,"imageUrl":2158},"Sequence variants identified in pre-miR-182. (A–D) Example of Sanger sequencing chromatography of patient DNA samples which are heterozygous for pre-miR-182 nt106 G/A alleles (A) and homozygous for pre-miR-182 nt106 A/A allele (B), heterozygous for pre-miR-182 nt105 C > T (C) and nt94 G > A variants (D). (E) Summary of the sequence variants of pre-miR-182 in the context of the hairpin structures of hsa-miR-182. Reference: miRbase.org.",[16244,16245,16277],{"#text":861},{"p":16246},[16247,16248,16251,16252,16255,16256,16259,16260,16263,16264,16267,16268,16271,16272,16276],{"#text":2110},{"bold":16249},[16250],{"#text":2114},{"#text":2116},{"bold":16253},[16254],{"#text":1782},{"#text":2121},{"bold":16257},[16258],{"#text":1788},{"#text":2126},{"bold":16261},[16262],{"#text":2130},{"#text":2132},{"bold":16265},[16266],{"#text":2136},{"#text":2138},{"bold":16269},[16270],{"#text":2142},{"#text":2144},{"ext-link":16273,":@":16275},[16274],{"#text":2148},{"@_ext-link-type":920,"@_xmlns:xlink":1796,"@_xlink:href":2150},{"#text":2152},{"#text":867},{"id":2093,"type":16225,"title":2168,"description":16279,"descriptionNodes":16280,"altText":19,"imageUrl":2212},"Sequence variants identified in pre-miR-96. (A–C) Example of Sanger sequencing chromatography of patient DNA samples which are heterozygous for pre-miR-96 nt36 T > C (A), nt39 C > T (B), and nt42 C > T variants (C). (D) Summary of the sequence variants of pre-miR-96 in the context of the hairpin structures of pre-miR-96. Reference: miRbase.org.",[16281,16282,16310],{"#text":861},{"p":16283},[16284,16285,16288,16289,16292,16293,16296,16297,16300,16301,16304,16305,16309],{"#text":2176},{"bold":16286},[16287],{"#text":2180},{"#text":2182},{"bold":16290},[16291],{"#text":1782},{"#text":2187},{"bold":16294},[16295],{"#text":1788},{"#text":2192},{"bold":16298},[16299],{"#text":2130},{"#text":2138},{"bold":16302},[16303],{"#text":2136},{"#text":2201},{"ext-link":16306,":@":16308},[16307],{"#text":2148},{"@_ext-link-type":920,"@_xmlns:xlink":1796,"@_xlink:href":2150},{"#text":2152},{"#text":867},{"id":3504,"type":16225,"title":3520,"description":16312,"descriptionNodes":16313,"altText":19,"imageUrl":3558},"Minimum free energy secondary structure prediction with base-pair probability on wild type (WT) hsa-pre-miR-182 (A) and hsa-pre-miR-96 (B) and their mutant forms with sequence variants. Data was compiled using publicly available software RNAfold (http://rna.tbi. univie.ac.at//cgi-bin/RNAWebSuite/RNAfold.cgi). Arrows indicate the sequence variant nucleotide. The brackets mark the areas with predicted changes of the secondary structure because of the sequence variants.",[16314,16315,16335],{"#text":1539},{"p":16316},[16317,16318,16321,16322,16325,16326,16329,16330,16334],{"#text":3528},{"bold":16319},[16320],{"#text":1782},{"#text":3533},{"bold":16323},[16324],{"#text":1788},{"#text":3538},{"italic":16327},[16328],{"#text":3542},{"#text":3544},{"ext-link":16331,":@":16333},[16332],{"#text":3548},{"@_ext-link-type":920,"@_xmlns:xlink":1796,"@_xlink:href":3550},{"#text":3552},{"#text":887},{"id":4444,"type":16225,"title":4454,"description":16337,"descriptionNodes":16338,"altText":19,"imageUrl":4489},"Inheritance patterns of the pre-miR-182 nt106 G/A allele and the expression levels of mature miR-182 in peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMNC) in a family with multiple cases of Stargardt disease -Family 4100. (A) the family pedigree. Proband II-2 and his brother II-4 are homozygous for the less common pre-miR-182 nt106 A allele (A/A); while II-5, III-1, 2, 3 are heterozygous (G/A) for this allele. Red: with Stargardt disease. Blue: with Complaint of autoimmune disease(s). (B,C) qRT-PCR on pre-miR-182 in the PBMNC of selected family members. *p \u003C 0.05; ***p \u003C 0.001.",[16339,16340,16359],{"#text":1539},{"p":16341},[16342,16343,16346,16347,16350,16351,16354,16355,16358],{"#text":4462},{"bold":16344},[16345],{"#text":1782},{"#text":4467},{"bold":16348},[16349],{"#text":4471},{"#text":4473},{"italic":16352},[16353],{"#text":2040},{"#text":4478},{"italic":16356},[16357],{"#text":2040},{"#text":4483},{"#text":887},{"id":4774,"type":16225,"title":4879,"description":16361,"descriptionNodes":16362,"altText":19,"imageUrl":4909},"Structural and primary sequence features of pri-miRNA stem of canonical miRNA hairpin (modified from Fang and Bartel, 2015; Nguyen et al., 2015; Bartel, 2018). A canonical miRNA hairpin includes a 35 +/− 1 bp stem, an unstructured terminal loop and singled stranded flanking regions. A basal UG motif, a mismatched GHG motif (H = A, C or U), an apical UGU motif, and flanking CNNC (N = any of the four nucleotides) motif enhance the processing and the precision of Drosha cleavage (red arrowheads). Purple arrowheads mark the sites for DICER cleavage.",[16363,16364,16382],{"#text":861},{"p":16365},[16366,16367,16371,16372,16376,16377,16381],{"#text":4887},{"xref":16368,":@":16370},[16369],{"#text":4757},{"@_ref-type":967,"@_rid":4759},{"#text":997},{"xref":16373,":@":16375},[16374],{"#text":4742},{"@_ref-type":967,"@_rid":4744},{"#text":997},{"xref":16378,":@":16380},[16379],{"#text":4784},{"@_ref-type":967,"@_rid":4786},{"#text":4903},{"#text":867},{"id":1512,"type":16384,"title":1522,"description":1530,"descriptionNode